==Trivia==
{{Trivia|date=July 2009}}
[[Image:Number 7 Roethlisburger Pittsburgh 3000px.jpg|right|thumb|The "#7 Roethlisburger".]]
[[Image:Peppis Store with Roethlisburger Sign.jpg|250px|right|thumb|Peppi's restaurant, home of the "Roethlisburger".]]
*Roethlisberger participated in the 2009 US Open Challenge with [[Michael Jordan]], [[Justin Timberlake]], and essay winner Larry Giebelhausen in a quest to break 100 on the [[Bethpage Black]] course. He shot an 81, the low of the group.
*He has multiple sandwiches named after him, which are usually a [[pun]] on his last name (which ends with "berger," similar to "hamburger"). Pittsburgh restaurant chain Peppi's sells the "Roethlisburger," which costs $7.00 (his football jersey number is 7).<ref>[http://www.campusfood.com/restaurant.asp?campusid=33&mlid=258570 "Peppi's Old Tyme Sandwich Shop menu"]</ref> A Findlay, Ohio restaurant Tony's also sells a "Roethlisburger," as does Brick Street in Oxford, Ohio.<ref>Rovell, Darren. [http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=1916354 "Roethlisberger in demand"]. [[ESPNEWS|ESPN.com]]. 4 November 2004.</ref>
*He is the second-youngest quarterback to win two Super Bowls.<ref>Stat given at the end of the Super Bowl game on 2/1/2009 NBC</ref>
*His surname "Roethlisberger" (Swiss-German spelling: R<U+00F6>thlisberger) is of Swiss origin with roots in the village of Geissbuehl [[Lauperswil]], Switzerland.<ref>Fleming, David. [http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/print?id=1970310&type=story "For whom the Ben tolls"]. [[ESPNEWS|ESPN.com]]. 19 January 2005.</ref><ref>The Associated Press. [http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/dailycourier/news/s_451853.html "Steelers' Roethlisberger discovers his Swiss roots"]. [[Associated Press]]. 12 May 2006 .</ref> He is a spokesman for Swiss Roots, a campaign intended to help Americans of Swiss origin reconnect with their Swiss ancestral heritage.<ref name=autogenerated3>Staff and wire reports. [http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/06129/688616-37.stm "Big Ben exploring his roots in Switzerland"]. [[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]] 9 May 2006.</ref> In May 2006, Roethlisberger and his family traveled to Switzerland for a week.<ref name=autogenerated3 /><ref>Fabus, Mike. [http://media3.steelers.com/article/63966/ "Roethlisberger's having fun in Switzerland"]. www.steelers.com 9 May 2006.</ref>
*He has his own line of barbecue sauce, Big Ben's BBQ.<ref name=bigben>[http://www.bigbensbbq.com Big Ben's BBQ<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
*His younger sister, Carlee Roethlisberger, plays women's basketball for the [[University of Oklahoma]].<ref>[http://soonersports.com/sports/w-baskbl/mtt/roethlisberger_carlee00.html SoonerSports.com Profile]</ref>
*Early in his career,  his name was shortened by 1 letter in the [[Madden NFL]] series, due to the game limiting the number of characters in a player's last name to 13 characters.
*He has appeared on the ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]'' twice, after each Super Bowl victory.<ref>[http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WCTKv_S4SeU&feature=channel_page Ben Roethlisberger gets a shave]</ref><ref>[http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=19vaoeNw72E Late Show - Super Bowl Champ Ben Roethlisberger]</ref>
*He introduced [[Kelly Clarkson]] at the [[2006 Grammy Awards]], one week after Pittsburgh won [[Super Bowl XL]].<ref>[http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=36BzDCD1rLI&feature=channel ben roethlisberger presents at the grammys]</ref>
*On October 5, 2009, Roethlisberger was the guest host of [[WWE Raw]] and was accompanied by his offensive line ([[Max Starks]], [[Chris Kemoeatu]], [[Justin Hartwig]], [[Trai Essex]], [[Darnell Stapleton]] and [[Willie Colon (American football)|Willie Colon]]).<ref>[http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/results/11092732/ Big Ben clocks in]</ref>

